Throughout the blocked Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile in a conflict of bloody resources in the 19th century is always well present, just like the desire to navigate the Pacific Ocean, once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, as Bolivia is awaiting a decision from the International Court of Justice, which will be issued on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
" Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course awaits a positive outcome," explains Roberto Calzadilla, Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on a large screen throughout the country, hoping that the Hague Court will vote in favour of Bolivia's request. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be required to negotiate a sovereign ocean crossing agreement in Bolivia.
