John Edward: Language skills are essential for the people of the world
The independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with new excellent review results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) are working to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools are working to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen and to replace them as citizens of the world.
As a sector of education capable of designing and implementing a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that contemporary languages remain popular and desirable subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, you speak to his heart."
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to create relationships and a relationship of trust with people from other countries.
Looking at the excellent results at this year's exams, it is noted that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade, A.
The data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of the students obtained the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as well as 72% of students who studied German, 69% of students who studied French and 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Languages as subjects are now organized as well as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that among the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital to preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of career choices, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this long-term competence.
Power to communicate directly with foreigners automatically places the multilingual person in front of its competitors.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults living in the United Kingdom, 75% of them did not have sufficient foreign language to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
That is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those of emerging economies, children will be better able to find rewarding employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Several of them will focus on conventional contemporary languages, while others will teach languages considered important to the United Kingdom for 2020, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child's preference, several languages will be available in independent schools, with specialized staff.
Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need for their success, regardless of what the future holds for them.
It is clear that languages in a world-wide trading environment are still of vital importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages must be regarded as "competences of international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
