While reiterating North Korea's well-known accusations of Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took steps, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made in Singapore on June 12 at the very first summit between a US President and a North Korean leader, when Kim committed to working for a "corean peninsula denuclearization" while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean war (1950-1953), but the United States stated that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
