Harvard: Students take rest classes
This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fight against the growing machinist tendency of studying eating caffeine all night long.
One professor noted that most students in the world's best university don't know how to take care of them
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is according to him the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a conference on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
At the end, a student approached me and said, "Why are they telling me only in the last year?"
She said that no one ever talked to her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
Published for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their well-being in general.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of the university's health services, stated that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that the students suffered from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The course time consists of various interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing various objects (coffee cups, curtains, basketball, books...) on which students click to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how the lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not change students' behaviour instantly.
However, in our view, they have the right to know this information - in the same way as you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are," added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride in " spending a white night" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students make sleeping a growing problem.
Having enough sleep and good quality should be the "secret weapon" of students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because the lack of sleep puts the brain in a mode of inanition, making them permanently hungry.
Raymond So, a Californian student in chemistry and physical biology aged 19, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year in Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and forced him to insist that he be offered at all campus.
He hoped that the next step would be to propose to all undergraduate students to follow a similar curriculum before joining the recognized institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students predict an alarm for both bedtime and wake-up hours, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and cause sleep disturbances.
