Fisheries and agriculture are the main pillars of the economy of Central Sulawesi province, and particularly of the Donggala coastal region.
Nickel extraction is also an important activity in the province, but it is mainly located in Morowali, on the opposite coast of the Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been affected by tsunamis several times since a century, according to the Indonesian Agency for Disaster Reduction.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of residences in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck the west of Donggala in 1996, killing nine.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific seismic fire circle and is regularly shaken by earthquakes.
Some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years are:
2004: A major earthquake, which occurred on 26 December on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh, triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, making 226 000 victims on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: Several violent earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatra from late March to early April.
A few hundred people died on the island of Nias off Sumatra.
2006: An earthquake of 6.8 magnitude reached southern Java, Indonesia's most inhabited island, triggering a tsunami that hit the southern coast and made nearly 700 victims.
2009: An earthquake of a magnitude of 7.6 shook the city of Padang, capital of the western province of Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake of 7.5 magnitude devastated one of the Mentawai islands off Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of more than 10 meters that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A superficial earthquake shook the Regency of Pidie Jaya in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, reminding the inhabitants of the devastating earthquake and the deadly tsunami of 2004.
No tsunami was caused this time, but more than 100 people were killed by the collapse of buildings.
2018: Major earthquakes shook the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mainly on the north side of the island.
