Point info on the red tide : Lower concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Commission on Fisheries and Wildlife of Florida indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular conditions of flowering are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - which causes concern for lower concentrations.
The red tide covers approximately 209 km (130 miles) of coasts from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in less sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or off, medium concentrations in Charlotte County and low concentrations in Lee County and off, high concentrations at the bottom or off of Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation was reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
